This program was terminated in 1996 but will continue to be shown for reporting purposes as loan balances remain outstanding.
The purchase of right-of-way is an eligible expense of the Federal-aid program and therefore a separate program is unnecessary.
A prohibition on further obligations is requested for 1999.
Statement of Operations (in millions of dollars) Identification code 69Â­8402Â­0Â­8Â­401 1996 actual 1997 actual 1998 est. 1999 est.
or credit support for project financing that may result in lower capital costs.
To capitalize a SIB, the State may deposit funds into either a highway or transit account or both.
To initiate a SIB highway account, a State may deposit up to 10 percent of most of its Federal-aid highway apportionments.
To fund a SIB transit account, a State may deposit up to 10 percent of some of its Federal transit capital funds.
A State then matches the SIB Federal capitalization funds in both modal accounts at its traditional matching ratio.
In 1997, State Infrastructure Banks received additional funding from the General Fund.
